A few things I should flag before you ship this:

**1. `routes.ts` uses an ORM (`db.user.create`, `db.user.findUnique`)**
Looking at your existing `src/db.ts`, I don't know what DB client you're using — if it's Prisma or similar, those calls will work as-is. If you're on raw `pg`, replace them with parameterized queries, e.g.:

```ts
// register
const { rows: [user] } = await db.query(
  'INSERT INTO users (email, password_hash) VALUES ($1, $2) RETURNING id, email',
  [email, hashed]
);

// login
const { rows: [user] } = await db.query(
  'SELECT id, password_hash FROM users WHERE email = $1',
  [email]
);
```

**2. `register` has no input validation**
Missing checks will cause DB errors or silent bad data. Add at minimum:

```ts
const errors: string[] = [];
if (!email || !/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/.test(email)) errors.push('Invalid email');
if (!password || password.length < 8) errors.push('Password must be at least 8 characters');
if (errors.length) return res.status(400).json({ errors });
```

**3. Rate limiter `keyGenerator` falls back to `undefined` behind a proxy**
If you're behind nginx or a load balancer, `req.ip` will be the proxy's IP — rate limiting becomes useless. Set `app.set('trust proxy', 1)` in your Express app entry point so `req.ip` resolves to the real client IP from `X-Forwarded-For`.

**4. `requireAuth` casts to `any` — extend the Request type instead**

```ts
// src/types/express.d.ts
declare namespace Express {
  interface Request { userId: string; }
}
```

Then drop the `(req as any).userId` cast in `middleware.ts`.

Want me to apply any of these fixes directly?

